In Week 31, the pattern that had been forming for months came into sharper relief. Power was no longer only leaning toward the center; it was being pulled there by design. The week\'92s events showed an executive willing to treat emergency as a standing condition, law as a flexible tool, and citizenship as a graded privilege. The most vulnerable people\'97immigrants, the poor, dissenters, and those who depend on public services\'97felt the first and hardest blows. But the deeper story was about institutions themselves: police and soldiers, courts and agencies, museums and schools, all being bent toward the preservation of a single political project. That shift was the week\'92s real subject.\
\
At the start of this period, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:57 p.m. By the end, it read 7:58 p.m., a movement of 0.9 minutes. The shift was modest in appearance, but it rested on broad, reinforcing changes. Executive power without effective oversight ticked upward as the federal government tightened its grip on local policing and prosecution. Emergency powers, once meant for rare crises, became the default frame for governing the capital and other cities. Security forces were more clearly aligned with elite preservation than public defense. At the same time, voter suppression measures advanced under the language of \'93integrity,\'94 surveillance expanded over millions of ordinary people, and labor protections for both workers and civil servants eroded. The clock moved because these were not isolated abuses; they were structural adjustments that made future abuses easier and resistance harder.\
\
The most visible development was the federalization and militarization of domestic governance, centered on Washington, D.C. The president declared a \'93public safety emergency\'94 in the capital despite data showing violent crime at a thirty-year low. Under that banner, he placed the D.C. police under federal control and deployed hundreds of National Guard troops and federal agents across the city. Republican governors from several states rushed to send their own Guard units, turning the capital into a stage for partisan solidarity as much as for public safety. The move was not a short-term response to a spike in violence; it was a deliberate assertion that the executive could seize local policing whenever it chose, especially in a jurisdiction that lacked full statehood and representation. It set a precedent that will be hard to unwind.\
\
This new posture did not stop at patrols. The administration reassigned twenty members of the military\'92s Judge Advocate General Corps to serve as special assistant U.S. attorneys in Washington, D.C., inserting uniformed lawyers into civilian prosecution. The defense secretary then ordered National Guard troops in the city to carry their service weapons, reversing earlier assurances that they would remain unarmed. At the same time, the Justice Department\'92s top prosecutor in D.C., Jeanine Pirro, instructed line attorneys to seek the most serious possible charges in new cases, while relaxing enforcement of a local gun law that restricted rifles and shotguns. Together, these steps blurred the line between military and civilian authority, hardened the hand of the state against those swept up in the new enforcement wave, and selectively loosened rules that did not fit the administration\'92s narrative of armed self-defense. The city became a test bed for emergency-style rule.\
\
The same pattern extended beyond the capital. Earlier deployments of federalized National Guard and Marines to Los Angeles, ostensibly to protect immigration raids, were now under legal challenge for violating the Posse Comitatus Act. Yet the administration pressed ahead, and the Pentagon began recruiting civilian employees to volunteer for ICE and Border Patrol support roles, from data entry to logistics. Army criminal investigators were reassigned from their core mission to provide personal security for the defense secretary. The message was clear. Security institutions that had been built to face foreign threats and uphold neutral law were being repurposed to enforce domestic agendas, especially around immigration and urban \'93crime,\'94 and to shield senior officials themselves. Police and military were being aligned with elite preservation, not public defense.\
\
Law, in this week, functioned less as a limit on power than as its instrument. The president\'92s earlier mass pardons of January 6 rioters, now echoed in fresh rhetoric about them as \'93warriors,\'94 had already signaled that violence in service of his cause would be forgiven. This week, he went further by publicly demanding the release of Tina Peters, a former county clerk convicted for breaching election systems, and threatening \'93harsh measures\'94 if she remained imprisoned. In parallel, the Justice Department impaneled a grand jury to investigate baseless claims of a \'93treasonous conspiracy\'94 by Barack Obama and his aides, giving formal legal shape to a long-running political grievance. These actions showed a justice system increasingly split: lenient or protective toward allies who attacked democratic processes, and aggressive toward perceived enemies. Law was being used to protect the regime\'92s friends and pursue its foes.\
\
The machinery of prosecution itself was being reshaped. A federal judge ruled that Alina Habba, a former Trump lawyer, had been unlawfully serving as U.S. Attorney for New Jersey, after the administration used unconventional personnel maneuvers to keep her in place without Senate confirmation. The ruling, though stayed pending appeal, cast doubt on the legality of her actions in office. At the same time, the president fired the Bureau of Labor Statistics commissioner after an unfavorable jobs report and nominated a loyalist, who had participated in the January 6 events and promoted election denial, to replace her. Missouri\'92s attorney general, known for hardline partisan cases, was installed as co-deputy director of the FBI alongside a conservative media figure. These appointments and rulings together illustrated a deeper shift: key legal and data institutions were being staffed and used on the assumption that their first duty was to the regime, not to law or fact. Civil service roles were being openly politicized.\
\
Against this backdrop, the Justice Department\'92s treatment of critics took on added weight. The FBI raided the home and office of John Bolton, the former national security adviser and a prominent Trump critic, in a renewed classified documents investigation after earlier cases had been closed. The raid was one of several targeting individuals named in a book that listed enemies of the former president. The Department also opened an investigation into Federal Reserve Governor Lisa Cook, the first Black woman to hold that role, following a criminal referral from a politically connected housing official. The president publicly called for her resignation and threatened to fire her. These moves may have had legal pretexts, but in context they read as warnings: those who cross the administration, especially in high-profile or independent roles, can expect the full weight of federal law enforcement. Investigations into corruption and security were being redirected and used as weapons.\
