Elections and representation were not left to voters alone; they were fought over in maps, rules, and access. In Texas, Republicans pushed through a mid-decade congressional redistricting plan, requested by the president, designed to add five Republican seats and diminish the voting power of people of color. When Democratic legislators fled the state to deny a quorum, the House speaker responded by assigning state troopers to monitor them, requiring \'93permission slips\'94 to leave the chamber, and threatening arrest for those who refused. Representative Nicole Collier, a Black Democrat, refused to sign, slept on the House floor, and later sued over what she described as illegal detention. The episode turned a legislative disagreement into a confrontation between elected representatives and armed state power. Protest rights inside the legislature itself were narrowed by security claims.\
