Courts in other states signaled their own willingness to bend rules. The Florida Supreme Court upheld a redistricting plan that stripped Black voters of influence in northern Florida, effectively nullifying a constitutional amendment against partisan and racial gerrymandering. In California, by contrast, Governor Gavin Newsom and the legislature responded to Texas\'92s map by passing their own mid-decade redistricting measures aimed at creating five new Democratic seats, to be ratified in a special election. This \'93Election Rigging Response Act\'94 bypassed the state\'92s independent redistricting commission and drew a lawsuit from Republicans who argued it violated procedural safeguards. The result was a national arms race in structural engineering: each side using the tools of law and process to lock in advantage, with voters and communities treated as pieces on a board. Representation was being shaped more by mapmakers and judges than by citizens.\
