These measures did more than enforce immigration law. They created a tiered legal order in which non-citizens, and even aspiring citizens, lived under constant surveillance and could lose status based on speech, associations, or the administration\'92s view of their ideology. The government also pursued a \'93third country\'94 deportation deal with Uganda and pushed for ICE to acquire its own fleet of planes, potentially doubling deportations. Hotels, including properties under the Marriott brand, were used as ad hoc detention sites despite corporate pledges, further obscuring the line between public custody and private space. In this system, immigration status was not just about paperwork; it was about alignment with the regime\'92s cultural and political expectations. Citizenship itself was being stratified by wealth, ideology, and heritage.\
