Surveillance and data were not confined to immigrants. The Justice Department opened a criminal investigation into whether D.C. police had manipulated crime statistics to make the city look safer, even as federal officials used claims of rising crime to justify the takeover. The White House launched an official TikTok account while pausing a congressionally mandated ban on the Chinese-owned platform, downplaying security concerns that had previously been treated as urgent. The Office of the Director of National Intelligence announced plans to cut its staff roughly in half, including scaling back the Foreign Malign Influence Center, even as the director revoked security clearances for 37 current and former intelligence officials accused of politicizing intelligence. The pattern was consistent: data and surveillance tools were expanded where they could monitor ordinary people and dissenters, and reduced where they might expose foreign interference or constrain the administration\'92s narratives. Algorithms were used to police ideology, not to inform policy.\
