The administrative state, once built to solve technical problems, was being reoriented toward ideological and donor priorities. At the Environmental Protection Agency, loyalists moved to rescind the 2009 endangerment finding that underpinned federal climate regulation, even as the administration repealed many green energy incentives and rewrote standards for renewable project credits. The Treasury Department\'92s rewrite threatened the viability of many clean energy developments, contributing to rising electricity prices and favoring fossil fuels. In health policy, the termination of major mRNA vaccine projects and public attacks on the American Academy of Pediatrics undermined scientific consensus and emboldened misinformation. FEMA\'92s new rule requiring disaster victims to have email addresses to apply for aid, combined with the end of paper payments and door-to-door canvassing, shifted the burden of access onto survivors least likely to be digitally connected. Public tragedy was made easier to monetize and harder to navigate.\
