Labor and economic protections eroded in quieter ways. The administration canceled union contracts for roughly 400,000 federal workers, including employees at the Department of Veterans Affairs, EPA, and Agriculture, after a court cleared the way. This stripped large segments of the civil service of collective bargaining rights and made them more vulnerable to political pressure. A new tax bill capped federal student loan borrowing and eliminated certain graduate loan programs, changes likely to narrow access to higher education for lower-income and professional-track students. The Congressional Budget Office reported that the same budget reconciliation bill would trigger nearly half a trillion dollars in Medicare cuts and close to a trillion in Medicaid cuts over the coming decade. These were not framed as attacks on democracy, but they deepened economic dependence and precarity, making it harder for many citizens to exercise their formal rights in practice. Labor protections were being chipped away to keep workers more atomized and dependent.\
