Information and memory were contested terrain. The president criticized the Smithsonian for focusing \'93too much\'94 on slavery and for portraying the country as \'93horrible,\'94 and directed his attorneys to review museum exhibits. The White House published an article attacking Smithsonian shows on race, slavery, trans identity, and immigration. These moves were not mere cultural skirmishes. They signaled an effort to recast national history away from confronting oppression and toward a triumphalist narrative that better served the regime\'92s self-image. At the same time, the administration fired a State Department press officer after he drafted a statement opposing forced relocations of Palestinians, and the Justice Department released heavily redacted transcripts of Ghislaine Maxwell\'92s interviews about Jeffrey Epstein\'92s associations while slowing broader Epstein disclosures. The public was given fragments of truth, curated in ways that protected powerful figures and aligned with the president\'92s desire to distance himself from scandal. Memory was being curated by power.\
