Yet the week also contained pockets of institutional resistance. A federal judge in Texas blocked a law requiring the Ten Commandments to be displayed in public school classrooms, citing the First Amendment\'92s separation of church and state. Courts ordered the closure of the \'93Alligator Alcatraz\'94 immigration jail in Florida within sixty days, citing environmental damage and legal violations, even as the state appealed. Another judge ruled that the State Department could not deny visas solely on the basis of the president\'92s travel ban for a group of applicants. In Oregon, the city of Grants Pass settled a lawsuit by agreeing to provide accessible camping spaces and services for unhoused people, despite a Supreme Court ruling that had allowed cities to criminalize camping. These decisions did not reverse the broader trend, but they showed that some judges and local actors still understood their role as a check on power and a guardian of rights. The legal order had not yet been fully captured.\
